When finding the argument, always consider the quadrant! The arctangent 
function only returns values in $\left(-\frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}\right)$, 
so you must adjust for quadrants II, III, and IV.

Multiplying by a complex number $w = r(\cos\theta + i\sin\theta)$ performs 
two geometric transformations:

| Operation | Effect on $z$ |
| Modulus $|w| = r$ | Scales (stretches or shrinks) $z$ by factor $r$ |
| Argument $\arg(w) = \theta$ | Rotates $z$ counterclockwise by angle $\theta$ |

**In other words:** $z \cdot w = $ (scale $z$ by $|w|$) then (rotate by $\arg(w)$)

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.8]
 % Axes
 (-3,0) – (4,0) node[right] {Re};
 (0,-2) – (0,4) node[above] {Im};

 % Original point z
 (Z) at (2,1);
 lldraw[AtlasTeal] (Z) circle (3pt);
 at (Z) {$z$};
 (0,0) – (Z);

 % Multiplier w (scale 1.5, rotate 60°)
 % Result: z*w has |z*w| = |z|*1.5, arg(z*w) = arg(z) + 60°
 % Original: |z| ≈ 2.24, arg(z) ≈ 27°
 % New: |zw| ≈ 3.35, arg(zw) ≈ 87°
 (ZW) at (0.17, 3.34);
 lldraw[AtlasCoral] (ZW) circle (3pt);
 at (ZW) {$z \cdot w$};
 (0,0) – (ZW);

 % Rotation arc
 (1.5,0.75) arc (26.6:86.6:1.67);
 at (1.2,1.8) { rotate by $\theta$};

 % Scale indicator
 (2.3,1.15) – (0.37,3.2);
 at (1.3,2.1) {scale by $r$};

 % Label for w
 at (3,-1.5) {$w = r(\cos\theta + i\sin\theta)$};
 at (3,-2) {$\bullet$ $r = |w|$ stretches};
 at (3,-2.5) {$\bullet$ $\theta = \arg(w)$ rotates};
tikzpicture
center

**Special cases:**

- $w = i = 1(\cos\frac{\pi}{2} + i\sin\frac{\pi}{2})$: Multiplying by $i$ **rotates 90°** (no scaling)

- $w = -1 = 1(\cos\pi + i\sin\pi)$: Multiplying by $-1$ **rotates 180°**

- $w = 2$: Multiplying by $2$ **scales by 2** (no rotation)

This geometric interpretation explains why $i^2 = -1$: rotating by 90° twice gives 180°!

